{"id":3776,"date":"2017-04-27T10:04:11","date_gmt":"2017-04-27T10:04:11","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/?p=3776"},"modified":"2018-09-22T19:41:47","modified_gmt":"2018-09-22T18:41:47","slug":"fab-historical-writers-justin-hill","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/fab-historical-writers-justin-hill\/","title":{"rendered":"Fab historical writers &#8211; Justin Hill"},"content":{"rendered":"\n\t<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/Justin-2-187x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"187\" height=\"200\" \/>For this, the last in my Spring series of &#8216;fab historical writers&#8217; features, I&#8217;m delighted to welcome Justin Hill to my blog. I met Justin several times last year at various spirited battle re-enactments around the 900th anniversary of 1066. His latest novel <em>Viking Fire<\/em> is about Harald Hardrada, hero of my own novel <em>The Constant Queen<\/em> which came out at almost the\u00a0same time so it was wonderful to discuss our favourite Viking and to consider our different versions of\u00a0his story. My novel centres around Harald&#8217;s wife Elizaveta and is a more &#8216;girlie&#8217; take on his life but both of us love Harald for his ambition and fire and both of us feel strongly that his is a story that has gone too long untold. I hope readers of either book will agree.<\/p>\nJustin did not start out writing about 1066, though his first historical novel, <em>Passing Under Heaven<\/em>, is set in China in the Tang Dynasty which is roughly contemporary to the Anglo Saxon Period. It\u00a0was inspired by the story of a female poet who was writing feminist poetry in the 9<sup>th<\/sup> century. The Tang Dynasty was unlike our imagination of China. The capital city, Xian, was in many ways the New York or London of its age. It was a time of artistic flowering and a time of unequalled freedoms for women in China, not to be repeated until the 20<sup>th<\/sup> Century. A woman could be independent as a Taoist priestess, concubine or courtesan and the poet in question, Yu Xuanji, managed to combine all three roles in a short life.<br \/>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/Justin-hill-200x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"150\" \/>Justin\u00a0revisited China when he\u00a0was asked to write the novelisation of the <em>Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon<\/em> sequel but other than he has since stuck with the UK as he became fascinated by Anglo Saxon England, working on a series that explores the narratives around the Battle of Hastings in 1066. The\u00a0first novel was <em>Shieldwall<\/em>\u00a0which deals with the end of Ethelred the Unready\u2019s reign and the much-less known Danish Conquest of 1016 and was a Sunday Times Book of the Year. The second,\u00a0<em>Viking Fire<\/em>, came out just last year and is getting stellar reader responses from readers. \u00a0As mentioned above, it recounts the life of perhaps the most extraordinary figure in the entire middle ages, Harald Hardrada, King of Norway, brother to Saint Olaf, mercenary, adventurer, reformer, and also the Last Viking. The Times picked it as one of their books of 2016 and I thoroughly enjoyed it. Why not <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.co.uk\/Justin-Hill\/e\/B000APOFKQ\/ref=dp_byline_cont_book_1\">check his books out for yourself<\/a><\/strong>, or read on to learn a bit more about Justin:\n<p><strong>Why and how did you become a writer?<\/strong><\/p>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/Justin-5-200x150.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"150\" \/>When I was little I used to want to be a fireman, and then it all changed when I was ten years old. I was in the rudimentary reading class, and I didn\u2019t like books. Then the boy next to me was reading a book called <em>The Hobbit<\/em> and it looked interesting, so I gave it a go, and loved it and went straight into <em>The Lord of the Rings<\/em>. I read the three books, the appendixes, everything \u2013 and I still remember the feeling of loss as I closed the book and the spell ended &#8211; the world, the people, their struggles had all felt so real for so long \u2013 and as it came to an end I felt a tug of grief and loss.<br \/>\nI remember thinking \u2018I want to do that.\u2019 To summon up worlds that felt real. So I decided, without knowing anything about it, that I wanted to be a writer.\n<strong>What\u2019s your favourite thing about being a writer?<\/strong><br \/>\nThe start of a novel is so full of promise and possibility\u2026 It\u2019s a fairly intense experience. I get a vision of what I want, a bit like St Paul with his Road to Damascus moment, and I get hugely inspired and excited about the story ahead.<br \/>\nIt\u2019s like a new lover. The possibilities are endless.\n<strong>And your least favourite?<\/strong><br \/>\nHalf way through, when the novel is frustrating me and I don\u2019t know how to make it work; and I feel like I have forgotten how to write. It feels very real at the time, but I\u2019ve been through it enough now to know it\u2019s a phase my books go through. And that it\u2019s part of making the story better, the characters more real, the pace more gripping.\n<strong>Why were you drawn to\u00a0the pre-1066 period?<\/strong><br \/>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/Justin-3-126x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"126\" height=\"200\" \/>I\u2019ve always loved the Anglo Saxon and Viking period. I grew up in York and it was hard not to identify with the Norse part of our history and heritage. Hastings is also one of our great national myths and tends to be recounted in simplistic pro-Norman or pro-Saxon tropes. I thought the story deserved something more realistic and interesting.\n<strong>Are there any other periods in history you fancy tackling?<\/strong><br \/>\nYes! Ancient Greek history is very appealing in terms of setting and language, although as a fan of Mary Renault, it would be hard to match her stories. But I\u2019ve a few ideas that I\u2019m mulling over.\n<strong>What do you think is the appeal of historical fiction?<\/strong><br \/>\nTraditional histories\n<strong>If there was one thing in history you could change what would it be?<\/strong><br \/>\nThe Norman Conquest. More specifically, I\u2019d be standing with a shield on Senlac Ridge on the late afternoon of 14<sup>th<\/sup> October, 1066, and I\u2019d give Harold Godwinson a nudge and say, \u2018Look out, Sir, there\u2019s an arrow coming.\u2019\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016.2-2-200x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"197\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Me (looking a bit mad) with Justin, James Aitcheson and Glynn Holloway at the Battle of Hastings re-enactment last year.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>If you&#8217;d like to find out more about Justin&#8217;s books, you can find him on his <strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.justinhillauthor.com\">website<\/a><\/strong>, follow him on <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/JHillAuthor\">twitter<\/a><\/strong> and <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/justinhillauthor\/\">facebook<\/a><\/strong>, or subscribe to his <strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.justinhillauthor.com\/get-in-touch\/\">mailing list<\/a><\/strong>. all comments welcome below or on my own<strong><a href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/joannacourtneyauthor?skip_nax_wizard=true\"> facebook page<\/a><\/strong>.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>For this, the last in my Spring series of &#8216;fab historical writers&#8217; features, I&#8217;m delighted to welcome Justin Hill to my blog. I met Justin several times last year at various spirited battle re-enactments around the 900th anniversary of 1066. His latest novel Viking Fire is about Harald Hardrada, hero of my own novel The&hellip;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":5,"featured_media":3780,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"_acf_changed":false,"slim_seo":{"title":"Fab historical writers - Justin Hill - Joanna Courtney","description":"For this, the last in my Spring series of 'fab historical writers' features, I'm delighted to welcome Justin Hill to my blog. I met Justin several times last ye"},"footnotes":""},"categories":[37],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-3776","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-historymatters"],"acf":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/3776","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/5"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=3776"}],"version-history":[{"count":0,"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/3776\/revisions"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/3780"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=3776"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=3776"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/joannacourtney.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=3776"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}